I"<p>If we perceive the world around as and derive representations from it, as the cognitive realist might argue, and if we can <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/visual-imagery-brightness-modulates-pupil-size">imagine looking at the world</a> from an arbitrary perspective, then why does our awareness default to first-person view? This is a dilemma explored by Greg Egan in “Seeing Through”. Why is it that we don’t have access to a vivid third-person view, based on the same (imperfect) representations?</p>
